# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-datasync
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:aws-datasync/amazon-web-services] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] As of 2011, "nearly 40 percent of data migration projects were over time, over budget, or failed entirely." Thus, proper planning is critical for an effective data migration.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] While the specifics of a data migration plan may vary—sometimes significantly—from project to project, IBM suggests there are three main phases to most any data migration project: planning, migration, and post-migration.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] During planning, dependencies and requirements are analyzed, migration scenarios get developed and tested, and a project plan that incorporates the prior information is created.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] During the migration phase, the plan is enacted, and during post-migration, the completeness and thoroughness of the migration is validated, documented, and closed out, including any necessary decommissioning of legacy systems.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] For applications of moderate to high complexity, these data migration phases may be repeated several times before the new system is considered to be fully validated and deployed.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] There is a difference between data migration and data integration activities.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] Data migration is a project through which data will be moved or copied from one environment to another, and removed or decommissioned in the source.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] During the migration (which can take place over months or even years), data can flow in multiple directions, and there may be multiple simultaneous migrations.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] The ETL (extract, transform, load) actions will be necessary, although the means of achieving these may not be those traditionally associated with the ETL acronym.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] Data integration, by contrast, is a permanent part of the IT architecture, and is responsible for the way data flows between the various applications and data stores—and is a process rather than a project activity.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] Standard ETL technologies designed to supply data from operational systems to data warehouses would fit within the latter category.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] Data is stored on various media in files or databases, and is generated and consumed by software applications, which in turn support business processes.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] The need to transfer and convert data can be driven by multiple business requirements, and the approach taken to the migration depends on those requirements.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] Four major migration categories are proposed on this basis.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] A business may choose to rationalize the physical media to take advantage of more efficient storage technologies.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] This will result in having to move physical blocks of data from one tape or disk to another, often using virtualization techniques.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] The data format and content itself will not usually be changed in the process and can normally be achieved with minimal or no impact to the layers above.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] Similarly, it may be necessary to move from one database vendor to another, or to upgrade the database software being used.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] The latter case is less likely to require a physical data migration, but this can happen with major upgrades.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] In these cases a physical transformation process may be required since the underlying data format can change significantly.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] This may or may not affect behavior in the applications layer, depending largely on whether the data manipulation language or protocol has changed.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] Furthermore, to allow the application to be sold to the widest possible market, commercial off-the-shelf packages are generally configured for each customer using metadata.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] Application programming interfaces (APIs) may be supplied by vendors to protect the integrity of the data they must handle.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] When no API is available, controlled browser tools such as Selenium or Playwright can be used to programmatically drive a web browser, extracting data from one web application and inserting it into another.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] Business processes operate through a combination of human and application systems actions, often orchestrated by business process management tools.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] When these change they can require the movement of data from one store, database or application to another to reflect the changes to the organization and information about customers, products and operations.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] Examples of such migration drivers are mergers and acquisitions, business optimization, and reorganization to attack new markets or respond to competitive threat.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] The first two categories of migration are usually routine operational activities that the IT department takes care of without the involvement of the rest of the business.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] The last two categories directly affect the operational users of processes and applications, are necessarily complex, and delivering them without significant business downtime can be challenging.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] A highly adaptive approach, concurrent synchronization, a business-oriented audit capability, and clear visibility of the migration for stakeholders—through a project management office or data governance team—are likely to be key requirements in such migrations.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] Migration, which focuses on the digital object itself, is the act of transferring, or rewriting data from an out-of-date medium to a current medium and has for many years been considered the only viable approach to long-term preservation of digital objects.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] Reproducing brittle newspapers onto microfilm is an example of such migration.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] Data portability is a concept to protect users from having their data stored in "silos" or "walled gardens" that are incompatible with one another, i.e. closed platforms, thus subjecting them to vendor lock-in and making the creation of data backups or moving accounts between services difficult.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] Data portability applies to personal data.
[src:aws-datasync/data-migration] It involves access to personal data without implying data ownership per se.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Replication in space or in time is often linked to scheduling algorithms.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Access to a replicated entity is typically uniform with access to a single non-replicated entity.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] The replication itself should be transparent to an external user.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] In a failure scenario, a failover of replicas should be hidden as much as possible with respect to quality of service.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] When one leader replica is designated via leader election to process all the requests, the system is using a primary-backup or primary-replica scheme, which is predominant in high-availability clusters.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] In comparison, if any replica can process a request and distribute a new state, the system is using a multi-primary or multi-master scheme.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] In the latter case, some form of distributed concurrency control must be used, such as a distributed lock manager.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Load balancing differs from task replication, since it distributes a load of different computations across machines, and allows a single computation to be dropped in case of failure.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Load balancing, however, sometimes uses data replication (especially multi-master replication) internally, to distribute its data among machines.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Backup differs from replication in that the saved copy of data remains unchanged for a long period of time.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Replicas, on the other hand, undergo frequent updates and quickly lose any historical state.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Replication is one of the oldest and most important topics in the overall area of distributed systems.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Data replication and computation replication both require processes to handle incoming events.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Processes for data replication are passive and operate only to maintain the stored data, reply to read requests and apply updates.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Computation replication is usually performed to provide fault-tolerance, and take over an operation if one component fails.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] In both cases, the underlying needs are to ensure that the replicas see the same events in equivalent orders, so that they stay in consistent states and any replica can respond to queries.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Database replication involves maintaining copies of the same data on multiple machines, typically implemented through three main approaches: single-leader, multi-leader, and leaderless replication.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] In single-leader (also called primary/replica) replication, one database instance is designated as the leader (primary), which handles all write operations.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] The leader logs these updates, which then propagate to replica nodes.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Each replica acknowledges receipt of updates, enabling subsequent write operations.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Replicas primarily serve read requests, though they may serve stale data due to replication lag – the delay in propagating changes from the leader.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] In multi-master replication (also called multi-leader), updates can be submitted to any database node, which then propagate to other servers.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] This approach is particularly beneficial in multi-data center deployments, where it enables local write processing while masking inter-data center network latency.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] However, it introduces substantially increased costs and complexity which may make it impractical in some situations.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] The most common challenge that exists in multi-master replication is transactional conflict prevention or resolution when concurrent modifications occur on different leader nodes.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Most synchronous (or eager) replication solutions perform conflict prevention, while asynchronous (or lazy) solutions have to perform conflict resolution.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] For instance, if the same record is changed on two nodes simultaneously, an eager replication system would detect the conflict before confirming the commit and abort one of the transactions.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] A lazy replication system would allow both transactions to commit and run a conflict resolution during re-synchronization.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Conflict resolution methods can include techniques like last-write-wins, application-specific logic, or merging concurrent updates.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] However, replication transparency can not always be achieved.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] When data is replicated in a database, they will be constrained by CAP theorem or PACELC theorem.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] In the NoSQL movement, data consistency is usually sacrificed in exchange for other more desired properties, such as availability (A), partition tolerance (P), etc.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Various data consistency models have also been developed to serve as Service Level Agreement (SLA) between service providers and the users.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Active (real-time) storage replication is usually implemented by distributing updates of a block device to several physical hard disks.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] This way, any file system supported by the operating system can be replicated without modification, as the file system code works on a level above the block device driver layer.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] It is implemented either in hardware (in a disk array controller) or in software (in a device driver).
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] The most basic method is disk mirroring, which is typical for locally connected disks.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] The storage industry narrows the definitions, so *mirroring* is a local (short-distance) operation.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] A replication is extendable across a computer network, so that the disks can be located in physically distant locations, and the primary/replica database replication model is usually applied.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] The purpose of replication is to prevent damage from failures or disasters that may occur in one location – or in case such events do occur, to improve the ability to recover data.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] For replication, latency is the key factor because it determines either how far apart the sites can be or the type of replication that can be employed.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] The main characteristic of such cross-site replication is how write operations are handled, through either asynchronous or synchronous replication; synchronous replication needs to wait for the destination server's response in any write operation whereas asynchronous replication does not.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Synchronous replication guarantees "zero data loss" by the means of atomic write operations, where the write operation is not considered complete until acknowledged by both the local and remote storage.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Most applications wait for a write transaction to complete before proceeding with further work, hence overall performance decreases considerably.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Inherently, performance drops proportionally to distance, as minimum latency is dictated by the speed of light.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] For 10 km distance, the fastest possible roundtrip takes 67 μs, whereas an entire local cached write completes in about 10–20 μs.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] In asynchronous replication, the write operation is considered complete as soon as local storage acknowledges it.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Remote storage is updated with a small lag.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Performance is greatly increased, but in case of a local storage failure, the remote storage is not guaranteed to have the current copy of data (the most recent data may be lost).
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Semi-synchronous replication typically considers a write operation complete when acknowledged by local storage and received or logged by the remote server.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] The actual remote write is performed asynchronously, resulting in better performance but remote storage will lag behind the local storage, so that there is no guarantee of durability (i.e., seamless transparency) in the case of local storage failure.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Point-in-time replication produces periodic snapshots which are replicated instead of primary storage.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] This is intended to replicate only the changed data instead of the entire volume.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] As less information is replicated using this method, replication can occur over less-expensive bandwidth links such as iSCSI or T1 instead of fiberoptic lines.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Many distributed filesystems use replication to ensure fault tolerance and avoid a single point of failure.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Many commercial synchronous replication systems do not freeze when the remote replica fails or loses connection – behaviour which guarantees zero data loss – but proceed to operate locally, losing the desired zero recovery point objective.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Techniques of wide-area network (WAN) optimization can be applied to address the limits imposed by latency.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] File-based replication conducts data replication at the logical level (i.e., individual data files) rather than at the storage block level.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] There are many different ways of performing this, which almost exclusively rely on software.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] A kernel driver (specifically a filter driver) can be used to intercept calls to the filesystem functions, capturing any activity as it occurs.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] This uses the same type of technology that real-time active virus checkers employ.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] At this level, logical file operations are captured like file open, write, delete, etc.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] The kernel driver transmits these commands to another process, generally over a network to a different machine, which will mimic the operations of the source machine.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Like block-level storage replication, the file-level replication allows both synchronous and asynchronous modes.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] In synchronous mode, write operations on the source machine are held and not allowed to occur until the destination machine has acknowledged the successful replication.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Synchronous mode is less common with file replication products although a few solutions exist.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] File-level replication solutions allow for informed decisions about replication based on the location and type of the file.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] For example, temporary files or parts of a filesystem that hold no business value could be excluded.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] The data transmitted can also be more granular; if an application writes 100 bytes, only the 100 bytes are transmitted instead of a complete disk block (generally 4,096 bytes).
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] This substantially reduces the amount of data sent from the source machine and the storage burden on the destination machine.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Drawbacks of this software-only solution include the requirement for implementation and maintenance on the operating system level, and an increased burden on the machine's processing power.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Similarly to database transaction logs, many file systems have the ability to journal their activity.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] The journal can be sent to another machine, either periodically or in real time by streaming.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] On the replica side, the journal can be used to play back file system modifications.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] One of the notable implementations is Microsoft's System Center Data Protection Manager (DPM), released in 2005, which performs periodic updates but does not offer real-time replication.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] This is the process of comparing the source and destination file systems and ensuring that the destination matches the source.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] The key benefit is that such solutions are generally free or inexpensive.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] The downside is that the process of synchronizing them is quite system-intensive, and consequently this process generally runs infrequently.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] One of the notable implementations is rsync.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] In a paging operating system, pages in a paging file are sometimes replicated within a track to reduce rotational latency.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] In IBM's VSAM, index data are sometimes replicated within a track to reduce rotational latency.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Another example of using replication appears in distributed shared memory systems, where many nodes of the system share the same page of memory.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] This usually means that each node has a separate copy (replica) of a specific page.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Many classical approaches to replication are based on a primary-backup model where one device or process has unilateral control over one or more other processes or devices.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] For example, the primary might perform some computation, streaming a log of updates to a backup (standby) process, which can then take over if the primary fails.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] This approach is common for replicating databases, despite the risk that if a portion of the log is lost during a failure, the backup might not be in a state identical to the primary, and transactions could then be lost.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] A weakness of primary-backup schemes is that only one is actually performing operations.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Fault-tolerance is gained, but the identical backup system doubles the costs.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] 1985, the distributed systems research community began to explore alternative methods of replicating data.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] An outgrowth of this work was the emergence of schemes in which a group of replicas could cooperate, with each process acting as a backup while also handling a share of the workload.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Computer scientist Jim Gray analyzed multi-primary replication schemes under the transactional model and published a widely cited paper skeptical of the approach "The Dangers of Replication and a Solution".
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] He argued that unless the data splits in some natural way so that the database can be treated as *n* disjoint sub-databases, concurrency control conflicts will result in seriously degraded performance and the group of replicas will probably slow as a function of *n*.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Gray suggested that the most common approaches are likely to result in degradation that scales as *O(n³)*.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] His solution, which is to partition the data, is only viable in situations where data actually has a natural partitioning key.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] In the 1985–1987, the virtual synchrony model was proposed and emerged as a widely adopted standard (it was used in the Isis Toolkit, Horus, Transis, Ensemble, Totem, Spread, C-Ensemble, Phoenix and Quicksilver systems, and is the basis for the CORBA fault-tolerant computing standard).
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Virtual synchrony permits a multi-primary approach in which a group of processes cooperates to parallelize some aspects of request processing.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] The scheme can only be used for some forms of in-memory data, but can provide linear speedups in the size of the group.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] A number of modern products support similar schemes.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] For example, the Spread Toolkit supports this same virtual synchrony model and can be used to implement a multi-primary replication scheme; it would also be possible to use C-Ensemble or Quicksilver in this manner.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] WANdisco permits active replication where every node on a network is an exact copy or replica and hence every node on the network is active at one time; this scheme is optimized for use in a wide area network (WAN).
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Modern multi-primary replication protocols optimize for the common failure-free operation.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] Chain replication is a popular family of such protocols.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] State-of-the-art protocol variants of chain replication offer high throughput and strong consistency by arranging replicas in a chain for writes.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] This approach enables local reads on all replica nodes but has high latency for writes that must traverse multiple nodes sequentially.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] A more recent multi-primary protocol, Hermes, combines cache-coherent-inspired invalidations and logical timestamps to achieve strong consistency with local reads and high-performance writes from all replicas.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] During fault-free operation, its broadcast-based writes are non-conflicting and commit after just one multicast round-trip to replica nodes.
[src:aws-datasync/data-replication] This design results in high throughput and low latency for both reads and writes.
[src:aws-datasync/file-synchronization] In *one-way file synchronization*, also called mirroring, updated files are copied from a source location to one or more target locations, but no files are copied back to the source location.
[src:aws-datasync/file-synchronization] In *two-way file synchronization*, updated files are copied in both directions, usually with the purpose of keeping the two locations identical to each other.
[src:aws-datasync/file-synchronization] In this article, the term synchronization refers exclusively to two-way file synchronization.
[src:aws-datasync/file-synchronization] File synchronization is commonly used for home backups on external hard drives or updating for transport on USB flash drives.
[src:aws-datasync/file-synchronization] BitTorrent Sync, Dropbox, SKYSITE, Nextcloud, OneDrive, Google Drive and iCloud are prominent products.
[src:aws-datasync/file-synchronization] Some backup software also supports real-time file sync.
[src:aws-datasync/file-synchronization] The automatic process prevents copying already identical files and thus can be faster and save much time versus a manual copy, and is less error prone.
[src:aws-datasync/file-synchronization] However this suffers from the limit that the synchronized files must physically fit in the portable storage device.
[src:aws-datasync/file-synchronization] Synchronization software that only keeps a list of files and the changed files eliminates this problem (e.g. the "snapshot" feature in Beyond Compare or the "package" feature in Synchronize It!).
[src:aws-datasync/file-synchronization] It is especially useful for mobile workers, or others that work on multiple computers.
[src:aws-datasync/file-synchronization] It is possible to synchronize multiple locations by synchronizing them one pair at a time.
[src:aws-datasync/file-synchronization] If you need to do this, the most reliable way to set things up is to organize the machines into a "star topology," with one machine designated as the "hub" and the rest as "spokes," and with each spoke machine synchronizing only with the hub.
[src:aws-datasync/file-synchronization] for every pair of hosts that it synchronizes.
[src:aws-datasync/file-synchronization] Shared file access involves but should not be confused with file synchronization and other information synchronization.
[src:aws-datasync/file-synchronization] Internet-based information synchronization may, for example, use the SyncML language.
[src:aws-datasync/file-synchronization] Shared file access is based on server-side pushing of folder information, and is normally used over an "always on" Internet socket.
[src:aws-datasync/file-synchronization] File synchronization allows the user to be offline from time to time and is normally based on an agent software that polls synchronized machines at reconnect, and sometimes repeatedly with a certain time interval, to discover differences.
[src:aws-datasync/file-synchronization] Modern operating systems often include a local cache of remote files, allowing offline access and synchronization when reconnected.
[src:aws-datasync/file-synchronization] Consumer-grade file synchronization solutions are popular, however for business use, they create a concern of allowing corporate information to sprawl to unmanaged devices and cloud services which are uncontrolled by the organization.
[src:aws-datasync/file-synchronization] When using cloud services, data privacy risks can be mitigated by using a file synchronization solution that features end-to-end encryption instead of simple transport (HTTPS) or at-rest encryption.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] A NAS device is optimised for serving files either by its hardware, software, or configuration.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] It is often manufactured as a computer appliance – a purpose-built specialized computer.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] NAS systems are networked appliances that contain one or more storage drives, often arranged into logical, redundant storage containers or RAID.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] Network-attached storage typically provide access to files using network file sharing protocols such as NFS, SMB, or AFP.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] Accompanying a NAS are purpose-built hard disk drives, which are functionally similar to non-NAS drives but may have different firmware, vibration tolerance, or power dissipation to make them more suitable for use in RAID arrays, a technology often used in NAS implementations.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] For example, some NAS versions of drives support a command extension to allow extended error recovery to be disabled.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] In a non-RAID application, it may be important for a disk drive to go to great lengths to successfully read a problematic storage block, even if it takes several seconds.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] In an appropriately configured RAID array, a single bad block on a single drive can be recovered completely via the redundancy encoded across the RAID set.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] A NAS unit is a computer connected to a network that provides only file-based data storage services to other devices on the network.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] Although it may technically be possible to run other software on a NAS unit, it is usually not designed to be a general-purpose server.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] For example, NAS units usually do not have a keyboard or display, and are controlled and configured over the network, often using a browser.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] A full-featured operating system is not needed on a NAS device, so often a stripped-down operating system is used.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] NAS systems contain one or more hard disk drives, often arranged into logical, redundant storage containers or RAID.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] NAS uses file-based protocols such as NFS (popular on UNIX systems), SMB (Server Message Block) (used with Microsoft Windows systems), AFP (used with Apple Macintosh computers), or NCP (used with OES and Novell NetWare).
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] NAS units rarely limit clients to a single protocol.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] The key difference between direct-attached storage (DAS) and NAS is that DAS is simply an extension to an existing server and is not necessarily networked.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] As the name suggests, DAS typically is connected via a USB or Thunderbolt enabled cable.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] NAS is designed as an easy and self-contained solution for sharing files over the network.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] Both DAS and NAS can potentially increase availability of data by using RAID or clustering.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] Both NAS and DAS can have various amount of cache memory, which greatly affects performance.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] When comparing use of NAS with use of local (non-networked) DAS, the performance of NAS depends mainly on the speed of and congestion on the network.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] Most NAS solutions will include the option to install a wide array of software applications to allow better configuration of the system or to include other capabilities outside of storage (like video surveillance, virtualization, media, etc).
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] DAS typically is focused solely on data storage but capabilities can be available based on specific vendor options.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] NAS provides both storage and a file system.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] This is often contrasted with SAN (storage area network), which provides only block-based storage and leaves file system concerns on the "client" side.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] SAN protocols include Fibre Channel, iSCSI, ATA over Ethernet (AoE) and HyperSCSI.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] Despite their differences, SAN and NAS are not mutually exclusive and may be combined as a SAN-NAS hybrid, offering both file-level protocols (NAS) and block-level protocols (SAN) from the same system.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] A shared disk file system can also be run on top of a SAN to provide filesystem services.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] In the early 1980s, the "Newcastle Connection" by Brian Randell and his colleagues at Newcastle University demonstrated and developed remote file access across a set of UNIX machines.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] Novell's NetWare server operating system and NCP protocol was released in 1983.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] Following the Newcastle Connection, Sun Microsystems' 1984 release of NFS allowed network servers to share their storage space with networked clients.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] 3Com and Microsoft would develop the LAN Manager software and protocol to further this new market.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] 3Com's 3Server and 3+Share software was the first purpose-built server (including proprietary hardware, software, and multiple disks) for open systems servers.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] Inspired by the success of file servers from Novell, IBM, and Sun, several firms developed dedicated file servers.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] While 3Com was among the first firms to build a dedicated NAS for desktop operating systems, Auspex Systems was one of the first to develop a dedicated NFS server for use in the UNIX market.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] A group of Auspex engineers split away in the early 1990s to create the integrated NetApp FAS, which supported both the Windows SMB and the UNIX NFS protocols and had superior scalability and ease of deployment.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] This started the market for proprietary NAS devices now led by NetApp and EMC Celerra.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] In 2009, NAS vendors (notably CTERA networks and Netgear) began to introduce online backup solutions integrated in their NAS appliances, for online disaster recovery.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] By 2021, three major types of NAS solutions are offered (all with hybrid cloud models where data can be stored both on-premise on the NAS and off site on a separate NAS or through a public cloud service provider).
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] The first type of NAS is focused on consumer needs with lower-cost options that typically support 1–5 hot plug hard drives.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] The second is focused on small-to-medium-sized businesses – these NAS solutions range from 2–24+ hard drives and are typically offered in tower or rackmount form factors.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] Pricing can vary greatly depending on the processor, components, and overall features supported.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] The last type is geared toward enterprises or large businesses and are offered with more advanced software capabilities.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] NAS solutions are typically sold without hard drives installed to allow the buyer (or IT departments) to select the hard drive cost, size, and quality.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] Embedded-system-based NAS – using an ARM- or MIPS-based processor architecture and a real-time operating system (RTOS) or an embedded operating system to run a NAS server.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] The power consumption of this NAS type is fair, and functions in the NAS can fit most end-user requirements.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] Marvell, Oxford, and Storlink make chipsets for this type of NAS.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] Max FTP throughput varies from 20 MB/s to 120 MB/s.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] ASIC-based NAS – provisioning NAS through the use of a single ASIC chip, using hardware to implement TCP/IP and file system.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] There is no OS in the chip, as all the performance-related operations are done by hardware acceleration circuits.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] The power consumption of this type of NAS is low, as functions are limited to only support SMB and FTP.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] LayerWalker is the only chipset manufacturer for this type of NAS.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] NAS is useful for more than just general centralized storage provided to client computers in environments with large amounts of data.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] NAS can enable simpler and lower cost systems such as load-balancing and fault-tolerant email and web server systems by providing storage services.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] In the consumer market, NAS devices have evolved into "private cloud" solutions.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] They allow users to store multimedia data and back up files from various devices (such as smartphones and PCs) while retaining full data ownership.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] Unlike public cloud services, these private cloud setups typically do not require monthly subscription fees for storage capacity.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] Such consumer market appliances are now commonly available.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] Unlike their rackmounted counterparts, they are generally packaged in smaller form factors.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] The price of NAS appliances has fallen sharply in recent years, offering flexible network-based storage to the home consumer market for little more than the cost of a regular USB or FireWire external hard disk.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] Many of these home consumer devices are built around ARM, x86 or MIPS processors running an embedded Linux operating system.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] A **purpose-built backup appliance** (PBBA) is a kind of NAS intended for storing backup data.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] PBBAs typically include data deduplication, compression, RAID 6 or other redundant hardware components, and automated maintenance.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] A PBBA may also be called a **backup and disaster recovery appliance** or simply a **backup appliance**.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] Open-source NAS-oriented distributions of Linux and FreeBSD are available.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] These are designed to be easy to set up on commodity PC hardware, and are typically configured using a web browser.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] They can run from a virtual machine, Live CD, bootable USB flash drive (Live USB), or from one of the mounted hard drives.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] They run Samba (an SMB daemon), NFS daemon, and FTP daemons which are freely available for those operating systems.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] If the client can be granted access to the file requested, the client receives the network location of NASD disks and their capability.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] If the client is accessing the disk for the first time, it receives a time-limited key for the establishment of secure communication to the disk.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] The file manager informs the corresponding disk using an independent channel.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] From now on, the client directly accesses the NASD disks by giving the capability it received and further data transfers go through the network, bypassing the file manager.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] A **clustered NAS** is a NAS that is using a distributed file system running simultaneously on multiple servers.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] The key difference between a clustered and traditional NAS is the ability to distribute (e.g. stripe) data and metadata across the cluster nodes or storage devices.
[src:aws-datasync/network-attached-storage] Clustered NAS, like a traditional one, still provides unified access to the files from any of the cluster nodes, unrelated to the actual location of the data.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] The **aggregate throughput** is the sum of the data rates that are delivered over all channels in a network.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Throughput represents digital bandwidth consumption.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] The throughput of a communication system may be affected by various factors, including the limitations of the underlying physical medium, available processing power of the system components, end-user behavior, etc.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] When taking various protocol overheads into account, the useful rate of the data transfer can be significantly lower than the maximum achievable throughput; the useful part is usually referred to as goodput.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Users of telecommunications devices, systems designers, and researchers into communication theory are often interested in knowing the expected performance of a system.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] From a user perspective, this is often phrased as either "which device will get my data there most effectively for my needs?", or "which device will deliver the most data per unit cost?".
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Systems designers often select the most effective architecture or design constraints for a system, which drive its final performance.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] In most cases, the benchmark of what a system is capable of, or its *maximum performance* is what the user or designer is interested in.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] The term *maximum throughput* is frequently used when discussing end-user maximum throughput tests.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Maximum throughput is essentially synonymous with digital bandwidth capacity.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Four different values are relevant in the context of maximum throughput are used in comparing the *upper limit* conceptual performance of multiple systems.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] They are *maximum theoretical throughput*, *maximum achievable throughput*, *peak measured throughput*, and *maximum sustained throughput*.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] These values represent different qualities, and care must be taken that the same definitions are used when comparing different *maximum throughput* values.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Each bit must carry the same amount of information if throughput values are to be compared.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Data compression can significantly alter throughput calculations, including generating values exceeding 100% in some cases.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] If the communication is mediated by several links in series with different bit rates, the maximum throughput of the overall link is lower than or equal to the lowest bit rate.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] The lowest value link in the series is referred to as the bottleneck.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Maximum theoretical throughput is closely related to the channel capacity of the system, and is the maximum possible quantity of data that can be transmitted under ideal circumstances.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] In some cases, this number is reported as equal to the channel capacity, though this can be deceptive, as only non-packetized systems technologies can achieve this.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Maximum theoretical throughput is more accurately reported taking into account format and specification overhead with best-case assumptions.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] The **asymptotic throughput** (less formal **asymptotic bandwidth**) for a packet-mode communication network is the value of the maximum throughput function, when the incoming network load approaches infinity, either due to a message size, or the number of data sources.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] As with other bit rates and data bandwidths, the asymptotic throughput is measured in bits per second (bit/s) or (rarely) bytes per second (B/s), where 1 B/s is 8 bit/s.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Decimal prefixes are used, meaning that 1 Mbit/s is 1000000 bit/s.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Asymptotic throughput is usually estimated by sending or simulating a very large message (sequence of data packets) through the network, using a greedy source and no flow control mechanism (i.e., UDP rather than TCP), and measuring the volume of data received at the destination node.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Traffic load between other sources may reduce this maximum network path throughput.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Alternatively, a large number of sources and sinks may be modeled, with or without flow control, and the aggregate maximum network throughput measured (the sum of traffic reaching its destinations).
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] A well-known application of asymptotic throughput is in modeling point-to-point communication where message latency $T(N)$ is modeled as a function of message length N as $T(N)=(M+N)/A$ where A is the asymptotic bandwidth and M is the half-peak length.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] As well as its use in general network modeling, asymptotic throughput is used in modeling performance on massively parallel computer systems, where system operation is highly dependent on communication overhead, as well as processor performance.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] In these applications, asymptotic throughput is used modeling which includes the number of processors, so that both the latency and the asymptotic throughput are functions of the number of processors.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Where asymptotic throughput is a theoretical or calculated capacity, *peak measured throughput* is throughput measured on a real implemented system, or on a simulated system.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] The value is the throughput measured over a short period of time; mathematically, this is the limit taken with respect to throughput as time approaches zero.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] This term is synonymous with *instantaneous throughput*.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] This number is useful for systems that rely on burst data transmission; however, for systems with a high duty cycle, this is less likely to be a useful measure of system performance.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Maximum sustained throughput is the throughput averaged or integrated over a long time.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] For networks under constant load, this is likely to be the most accurate indicator of system performance.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] The maximum throughput is defined as the asymptotic throughput when the load is large.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] In packet-switched networks while packet loss is not occurring, the load and the throughput always are equal.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] The maximum throughput may be defined as the minimum load in bit/s that causes packet loss or causes the latency to become unstable and increase towards infinity.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Throughput is sometimes normalized and measured in percentage, but normalization may cause confusion regarding what the percentage is related to.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] *Channel utilization*, *channel efficiency* and *packet drop rate* in percentage are less ambiguous terms.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] The channel efficiency, also known as bandwidth utilization efficiency, is the percentage of the net bit rate (in bit/s) of a digital communication channel that goes to the achieved throughput.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] For example, if the throughput is 70 Mbit/s over a 100 Mbit/s Ethernet connection, the channel efficiency is 70%.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Channel utilization includes both the data bits and the transmission overhead in the channel.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] The transmission overhead consists of preamble sequences, frame headers and acknowledgment packets.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] In a simplistic approach, channel efficiency can be equal to channel utilization assuming that acknowledge packets are zero-length and that the communications provider will not see any bandwidth relative to retransmissions or headers.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Therefore, certain texts mark a difference between channel utilization and protocol efficiency.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] For example, the maximum frame size in Ethernet is 1526 bytes: up to 1500 bytes for the payload, eight bytes for the preamble, 14 bytes for the header, and 4 bytes for the trailer.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] An additional minimum interframe gap corresponding to 12 bytes is inserted after each frame.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] This corresponds to a maximum channel utilization of 1526 / (1526 + 12) × 100% = 99.22%, or a maximum channel use of 99.22 Mbit/s inclusive of Ethernet datalink layer protocol overhead over a 100 Mbit/s Ethernet connection.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] The maximum throughput or channel efficiency is then 1500 / (1526 + 12) = 97.5%, exclusive of the Ethernet protocol overhead.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] The throughput of a communication system will be limited by a number of factors.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] The maximum achievable throughput (the channel capacity) is affected by the bandwidth in hertz and signal-to-noise ratio of the analog physical medium.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Limited current drive capability in communications equipment can limit the effective signal-to-noise ratio for high capacitance links.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Despite the conceptual simplicity of digital information, all electrical signals traveling over wires are analog.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] The analog limitations of wires or wireless systems inevitably provide an upper bound on the amount of information that can be sent.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] The dominant equation here is the Shannon–Hartley theorem, and analog limitations of this type can be understood as factors that affect either the analog bandwidth of a signal or as factors that affect the signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] The bandwidth of twisted pair cabling used by Ethernet is limited to approximately 1 GHz, and PCB traces are limited by a similar amount.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Digital systems refer to the *knee frequency*, the amount of time for the digital voltage to rise from 10% of a nominal digital 0 to a nominal digital 1 or vice versa.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Large data loads that require processing impose data processing requirements on hardware.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] For example, a gateway router must examine and perform routing table lookups on billions of packets per second.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] CSMA/CD and CSMA/CA backoff waiting time and frame retransmissions after detected collisions slows transmissions.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] This may occur in Ethernet bus networks and hub networks, as well as in wireless networks.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Flow control, for example, in the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) protocol, affects the throughput if the bandwidth-delay product is larger than the TCP window.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] In that case, the sending computer must wait for acknowledgement of the data packets before it can send more packets.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] TCP congestion avoidance controls the data rate.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] A so-called *slow start* occurs in the beginning of a file transfer, and after packet drops caused by router congestion or bit errors in, for example, wireless links.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Ensuring that multiple users can harmoniously share a single communications link requires some kind of equitable sharing of the link.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] If a communication link offering data rate *R* is shared by *N* active users, ideally, every user can typically achieve a throughput of approximately *R/N*.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Network schedulers in routers and switches ultimately determine how bandwidth is shared.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] If fair queuing is not provided, users that send large packets will get higher bandwidth.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Some users may be prioritized in a weighted fair queuing (WFQ) algorithm if differentiated or guaranteed quality of service (QoS) is provided.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] In some communications systems, such as satellite networks, only a finite number of channels may be available to a given user at a given time.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Channels are assigned either through preassignment or through Demand Assigned Multiple Access (DAMA).
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] In these cases, throughput is quantized per channel, and unused capacity on partially utilized channels is lost.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] The maximum throughput is often an unreliable measurement of effective bandwidth, for example the file transmission data rate in bits per seconds.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] The achieved throughput is often lower than the maximum throughput.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Protocol overhead affects the effective bandwidth.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] In schemes that include forward error correction codes, the redundant error code is normally excluded from the throughput.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] An example in modem communication, where the throughput is typically measured in the interface between the Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP) and the circuit-switched modem connection.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] In this case, the maximum throughput is often called net bit rate or useful bit rate.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] To determine the actual data rate of a network or connection, the goodput measurement definition may be used.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] For example, in file transmission, the goodput corresponds to the file size (in bits) divided by the file transmission time.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] The goodput is the amount of useful information that is delivered per second to the application layer protocol.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Dropped packets or packet retransmissions, as well as protocol overhead, are excluded.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Because of that, the goodput is lower than the maximum throughput.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Often, a block in a data flow diagram has a single input and a single output, and operates on discrete packets of information.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Examples of such blocks are fast Fourier transform modules or binary multipliers.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Because the units of throughput (e.g., messages per second) are the reciprocal of the unit for propagation delay (e.g., seconds per message), throughput can be used to relate a computational block to a communications channel, simplifying system analysis.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] In wireless networks or cellular systems, the system spectral efficiency in bit/s/Hz/area, bit/s/Hz/site or bit/s/Hz/cell units, is the maximum aggregate throughput divided by the analog bandwidth and some measure of the system coverage area.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Throughput over analog channels is determined by the modulation scheme, the signal-to-noise ratio, and the available bandwidth.
[src:aws-datasync/throughput] Since throughput is normally defined in terms of quantified digital data, the term *throughput* is not normally used; the term *bandwidth* is more often used instead.
